'''The SMArt 155''' is a German [[155&nbsp;mm]] [[Guided artillery shell|guided artillery round]] designed for a long-range, [[indirect fire]] [[top attack|top-attack]] role against armoured vehicles. The projectile was developed in 1989 by [[Diehl BGT Defence]] in Überlingen, Germany, with [[Rheinmetall]] and started full-rate production for the German Army in 1998. It consists of a {{convert|47|kg|adj=on}} heavy artillery projectile containing two autonomous, sensor-fused, "[[fire-and-forget]]" submunitions.
Due to the submunitions, it has been considered by some to be a [[cluster munition]]. As of 2008, representatives of the German defense ministry have referred to it as not being classified as submunition weapons, which were prohibited by the 2008 [[Convention on Cluster Munitions]].

==Description==
The name SMArt 155 is a contraction of its German name, ''Suchzünder Munition für die Artillerie 155'' (meaning "sensor-fuse munition for 155mm artillery").

==History==
The projectile was developed in 1989,<ref>{{Cite book |last=Jenzen-Jones |first=N.R. |title=Munitions Employing Sensor-fuzed Submunitions: Do they Comply with the Convention on Cluster Munitions? |publisher=[[Armament Research Services]] |year=2021 |isbn=978-0-6485267-9-7 |location=Australia |pages=19 |language=English}}</ref> and GIWS started full-rate production for the German Army in 1998.<ref name="atk_1"/>

==Design==
[[image:Smart155 detail.svg|center|Schematic of the SMArt 155 round]]
[[File:GIWS SMArt 155 cutaway Klietz 2025.jpg|thumb|right|Cut away photo of SMArt 155 submunition.]]
SMArt 155 is a 155&nbsp;mm NATO artillery round designed to be fired from the [[Panzerhaubitze 2000]] and the [[M109 howitzer]]s, including the Paladin variant.<ref name="defense-update">{{cite web | url=https://defense-update.com/20080810_smart.html | title=SMArt Sensor-Fuzed Ammunition for 155mm guns | publisher=Defense-Update.com | date=10 August 2008 | accessdate=13 July 2022 | archive-date=13 July 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220713200803/https://defense-update.com/20080810_smart.html | url-status=live }}</ref> It consists of a {{convert|47|kg|adj=on}} heavy artillery projectile containing two autonomous, sensor-fused, [[fire-and-forget]] submunitions.<ref name="defense-update" /> The submunitions each contain a high-penetration [[Explosively formed penetrator|EFP]] warhead for use against heavy [[armoured fighting vehicle]]s such as [[main battle tank]]s. The EFP warhead uses a heavy metal liner.<ref name="GiwsDesign">{{cite web | url=http://www.giws.de/en/smart/design.html | title=SMArt 155 Family of intelligent munition | publisher=GIWS mbh | accessdate=4 December 2010 | archive-date=22 September 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110922092420/http://www.giws.de/en/smart/design.html | url-status=dead }}</ref>

After the submunition is released, it opens a parachute. While slowly descending, the submunition rotates, scanning the area below with an [[infra-red|infrared]] sensor and a [[millimeter wave]] radar.<ref name="defense-update" /><ref name="GiwsDesign" />

The utilization of several types of sensors allows SMArt 155 to be used in all terrain types and weather conditions.<ref name="GiwsProducts">{{cite web | url=http://www.giws.de/en/smart/system.html | title=SMArt 155: A new Dimension for Artillery | publisher=GIWS mbh | accessdate=4 December 2010 | archive-date=15 March 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315180949/http://www.giws.de/en/smart/system.html | url-status=dead }}</ref>

==Operation==
[[image:Smart155 overview.svg|700px|center]]1: A SMArt 155 round is fired from a standard [[155 mm caliber#NATO standard|NATO 155mm]] artillery tube.

2: The round flies on a [[External ballistics|ballistic]] arc, with a range of {{convert|27.5|km|mi|1}}.<ref name="deagel">{{cite web |date=December 30, 2010 |title=SMArt 155 |url=http://www.deagel.com/Projectiles/SMArt-155_a001141001.aspx |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111223153750/http://www.deagel.com/Projectiles/SMArt-155_a001141001.aspx |archive-date=23 December 2011 |accessdate=7 January 2011 |publisher=deagel.com}}</ref>

3: Mid-flight, a [[Fuze#Time|time fuze]] ignites an ejection charge in the nose that pushes the submunitions out of the base of the projectile.

4: The submunitions deploy parachutes and independently fall over the target area while scanning for targets.

5: Once a submunition detects a target vehicle beneath it, it detonates its explosive payload. This creates a high-velocity [[explosively formed projectile]] which strikes the target vehicle from above, where the armour is relatively weak, for maximum effect.

==Competing systems==
US artillery largely deploys the [[M712 Copperhead]] laser-guided round for the anti-tank role.

GIWS formed a partnership with US defence contractor [[Alliant Techsystems]], hoping to sell SMArt 155 to the United States armed forces; as of 2002, no sale had been made.<ref name="atk_1">{{cite web  |url=http://atk.mediaroom.com/index.php?s=118&item=80  |title=ATK Partner GIWS Achieves 100-Percent Reliability In Tests of Extended Footprint SMArt 155 Munition Precision-Guided Projectile is Part of ATK's Newly Formed Precision Systems Group  |publisher=ATK press release  |date=May 9, 2002  |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714065149/http://atk.mediaroom.com/index.php?s=118&item=80  |archivedate=July 14, 2011  }}</ref> The US developed the similar [[Sense and Destroy ARMor|M898 SADARM]] system (which also descended on a ballute to attack the top surfaces of armoured vehicles), but this was discontinued in favour of the [[Global Positioning System|GPS]] guided [[M982 Excalibur]] round.

SMArt 155 is very similar to the [[Bofors 155 Bonus|155 BONUS]] system; BONUS descends on a system of winglets rather than a parachute.

